                <note rend="inline" type="source">710.G Commercial Agreement/27: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-19T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 19, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>93. Your 239, September 15, 3 p.m.; 243 September 18, 3 p.m. Department gratified
                    with the way you are handling this question, and hopes for the minimum of any
                    opposition.</p>
                <p>Without seeming to push the matter, please follow developments closely and take
                    advantage of any opportunities that may arise to explain the Agreement for
                    refraining from invoking the most-favored-nation clause and discreetly endeavor
                    to ascertain and answer or report to the Department any objections that may be
                    offered. Department would appreciate being kept currently informed.</p>
                <p>Department is not at present approaching any Governments through American
                    Missions at their capitals.</p>
                <p>I expect to sign the Agreement <hi rend="italic">ad referendum</hi> on Thursday,
                    September 20.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
